l,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe olfactory bulb is most closely associated with the \u003Cstrong\u003Eethmoid\u003C/strong\u003E bone, specifically resting on the cribriform plate of the ethmoid. This anatomical relationship is crucial for the transmission of olfactory information from the nasal cavity to the brain. The cribriform plate allows the passage of the olfactory nerves from the nasal epithelium to the olfactory bulb.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Efrontal\u003C/strong\u003E bone forms the anterior part of the skull and the forehead but does not directly support the olfactory bulb.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esphenoid\u003C/strong\u003E bone is located more posteriorly in the skull and houses the sella turcica, which holds the pituitary gland, but it is not directly related to the olfactory bulb.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ezygomatic\u003C/strong\u003E bone is part of the facial skeleton, forming the cheekbones, and does not have a direct relationship with the olfactory bulb.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eparietal\u003C/strong\u003E bones form the sides and roof of the cranial cavity and are not involved in the support of the olfactory bulb.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The olfactory bulb is located on the cribriform plate of the ethmoid bone.","The ethmoid bone is a key structure in the anterior cranial fossa, supporting the olfactory bulb and nerves.","Understanding the anatomical relationships of cranial structures is crucial for diagnosing and managing head injuries and sinus-related conditions."],"references":["Singh, V. (2023). Textbook of Anatomy-Head, Neck and Brain, Volume III-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Patestas, M. A., \u0026 Gartner, L. P. (2016). A textbook of neuroanatomy. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Patel, C. R., Fernandez-Miranda, J. C., Wang, W. H., \u0026 Wang, E. W. (2016). Skull Base Anatomy. Otolaryngologic clinics 